 margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The mining industry itself must engage better with civil society and NGOs in order to communicate the centrality of metals and minerals to daily life and what the industry is doing to ensure it operates in a responsible a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd sustainable manner</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government support of the extractives industries is essential to securing UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> access to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">metals, minerals and power</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> critical to modern society</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK’s position as a centre for extractive expertise is being threatened by the reduction i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n global commodity prices and the inability to secure financial support for resource projects. The government must continue measures that reinvigorate the economy and encourage investment</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The signing of the EITI has reinforced the UK’s position as a global</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> leader in accountable, transparent and responsible business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and adequate regulation is enquired to ensure that London listed companies comply with these standards</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About me and my submission:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I make this submission on behalf of Mining On</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Top; the conference and training division of IntierraRMG. IntierraRMG are the leading data supplier to the global mining industry with offices in Australia, across Canada, in Sweden and London. Mining On Top was launched in January 2013 in order to consol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">idate the company’s events and trainings under a single brand. I am the leader of the Mining On Top business.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> This submission will focus largely on the contribution of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">metals and minerals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exploration and mining industry to the UK economy.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I have a BA i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n Social Ethics and worked in Financial Services for many years before stumbling int</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o the mining industry in January 2010. I have organised more than 30 mining focused conferences</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, seminars</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and trainings in the UK, Europe and Africa. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The reason for the Mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ning On Top submission of evidence is that we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">passionately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">believe that mining is an essential enabler of social and economic development in developing nations where the mineral endowment is often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rich and underexploited</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The UK industry must be strong and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> transparent in order to be at the forefront of the facilitation of this development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and to ensure the supply of the resources critical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the UK population and business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Recommendations:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK government must support and foster the UK’s involvement in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the global extractives industries by ensuring that economic conditions are stable and conducive to business</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK government must keep an open mind and listen to extractive com</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">panies with equal enthusiasm as they do to NGOs and pressure groups in order to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> better understand the industry and its contribution to UK society, both financially and in terms of providing materials that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are essential to everyday life</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Light touch but rigorous regulation to ensure the integrity of extractives companies listed and/or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">headquartered in the UK is essential to maintaining the Nation’s position as a global leader in transparency and integrity </span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Answers:</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How does the UK based extractive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> industries support employment A) in the UK and B</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">) for UK citizens overseas?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are four types of structures that make a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contribution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the UK economy from extractives. They are:- </span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 13.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK companies extracting UK resources</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">International companies extracting UK resources</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK listed/ headquartered companies extracting international </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resources</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 14.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Internationally headquartered/ listed companies extracting international resources</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">From the first two categories the contribution to the UK economy is not that high (although in the past the mining industry in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contributed significantly, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e contribution of North Sea oil and gas has been substantial and shale gas is set to make a substantial contribution </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the economy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the future).</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Today, the biggest economic contribution comes from the third and fourth categories. It is no coincidence th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at global companies like BHP Billiton and Anglo American have decided to list and headquarter in London; London provides the best access to capital markets, investment, expertise and extractive support services of anywhere in the world. Other extractives c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">entres (such as Perth, Vancouver, Calgary, Nordics, Houston and Johannesburg) do not come close to the depth and history and experience, built up over many centuries, which is found in the UK. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK engineering expertise is regarded as some of the most relia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ble on the planet and an essential component of any successful mining project. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This expertise is utilised by UK and international companies. Every day Canadian and Australian mining companies are in London to secure expertise, finance and services. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has historically been home to some of the world’s most respected mining engineering and geological colleges with Imperial College, Royal School of Mines, Cardiff and Cambourne.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK based extractives industry supports employment in the UK in many indu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stries. Clearly in varied roles working within UK based mining companies, but also within financial services – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">metals traders, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">analysts, brokers, investment bankers, asset and wealth managers, stock brokers, fund managers and in private equity and venture </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">capital. Insurance, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">law and accounting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> large area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of employment. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Other services such as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recruitment, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PR/ IR </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">geological, engineering, risk and environmental consultancy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are also represented. Data, publications, investor presentations, conferences and training are another </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are where the UK leads</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Finally, but not exclusively, engineering, equipment and infrastructure and building services also contribute to the industry. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These include </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">building, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">explosives, piping, drills, water management, power generators, steel products and a large variety of other products and services.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I am not sure of the total universe </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of UK people involved in the industry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">but I do know that there ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e over one thousand Women in Mining members in the UK and women are not highly represented in the industry.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">B.There are a high number of UK citizens working abroad in the mining industry and many have migrated to mining boom areas, such as Western Australi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a, Africa and South America to fill skills shortages in those regions and to supply expertise in the form of consultancy and services.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Unsubstantiated estimates </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">claim </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that the contribution to the UK economy of the wider mining and support industry is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">twenty percent. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2.Does UK industry benefit more widely from the UK’s position as a centre for extractive industries i.e. In sales of machinery and services to international businesses in the sector?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK industry benefits more widely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> from its position as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">centre of excellence for extractives in economic terms (as discussed above) but also from innovations which are generated by the need to solve complex engineering issues in mining projects.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> These innovations feed into the general engineering offering in the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mining projects are complex engineering initiatives. Bulk commodities – coal and iron ore -are really transportation projects; bauxite is a power story and much processing has a heavy reliance on chemical and water and waste treatment. For this reason </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">engi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">neering consultancy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">companies such as Mott MacDonald have recently established a mining division to capitalise on these opportunities.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If you attend a large mining conference, such as the Prospectors and Developers Association Conference or Mining Indaba y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ou will see many familiar UK engineering and equipment companies represented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> who are looking to earn additional clients in the mining sector</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Another important point to make is that the jobs created by the mining industry are not just London centric. Consu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ltant Weir is based in Todmorden</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with a head office in Glasgow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, SRK in Cardiff, ERM in Cambridge etc.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3.Has the boom in London-listed extractive companies with businesses overseas over the last two decades resulted in a strengthening in the UK’s competitiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e position in this sector?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The boom in London listed extractive companies with businesses overseas has occurred due to the predominant position of the UK as the hub of the global mining industry and has reinforced that position. The Toronto Stock Exchange </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has more listed mining companies than the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at 1638 compared with 179, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">but their average size</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in terms of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> market capitalisation and share price tends to be smaller</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (£1129m cf $170m)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. No other exchanges come close.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.What are the corporate governance conce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rns raised by the number of extractive industries companies listed in the UK? Are there reputational risks for the UK and UK financial institutions in being a centre for such businesses?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some recent, high profile cases of alledged corporate governance irre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gularities by London listed foreign extractive companies have caused co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncern but should not provoke </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">over</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reaction.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There are parallels with recent issues in the banking sector but no one believes that the UK’s position as the leading financial centre in t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he world be scaled-back but rather that better governance is introduced to ensure that this position is protected and proper due-diligence procedures are followed.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Similarly with mining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sufficient and auditable but light-touch corporate governance legislation is essential. In the past Canada suffered a similar high profile extractives corporate governance scandal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the 1990’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(Br</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e-X</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) but has survived as a recognised centre of mining.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector? Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive industries and NGOs?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the past the extractive sector in general has been too closed. This is prob</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ably due to a lack of understanding of the importance of engaging with civil society and a lack of knowledge of how to engage. This has led to mistrust and a lack of awareness in wider society of the centrality of minerals and metals to everyday life. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Con</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sequently, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mining companies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">even more reticent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to put their heads above the parapet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has enabled NGOs to set the agenda and perceptions of the industry.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This situation is beginning to change among the more forwa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rd thinking mining companies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as ga</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ining social license to operate becomes more important a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> civil society becomes increasingly powerful. At the same time it sometimes appears that there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unwillingness</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> amongst NGOs to engage with the mining industry and listen to an alternative viewpoint</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The recent Mining On Top: Africa – London Summit in June had African Mining Ministers, UK MPs, miners, and industry suppliers around one table with NGOs debating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sustainability and how</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mining </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can be used to foster</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> social and economic development of the c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ontinent.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The event was one of the first to have all stakeholders around the same table to discuss these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">issues and all the participants were amazed to discover how much common ground they had once they actually listened to each other.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Participants </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">included the London companies Anglo American and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> First Quantum Minerals Limited and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Canadian companies with UK board members, shareholders and management Banro Resources, and Montero Mining. They were joined by NGOs including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PWYP, WWF, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Africare, Internati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onal Alert</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Global Witness dropped out days before the event</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Ministers from six African countries including Ghana, Rwanda and South Sudan attended alongside James Duddridge and Eric Joyce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> MP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Other organisations participating included U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nited Nations Econ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">omic Council for Africa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, EITI,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">International Council on Metals and Mining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The International Institute for the Environment and Development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and UKTI.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In 2014 the event will also feature a focus on the development of regional infrastructure, precipitated by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the need to support mining projects but, that also support community and agribusiness development in those areas. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Anglo American is a leader in sustainability and a good example of best practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> among mining companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The International Council on Metals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and Mining, an organisation sponsored by large mining companies, also sets many of the standards that the industry adheres to. The International Institute for the Environment and Development is a think-tank that leads much of the thinking around sustainabi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lity issues.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6.Does the UK have the skills base to remain a centre for the extractive industries and to ensure that UK based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such as shale gas? </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A lack of support for the industry, combined with lower </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">commodity prices and the reduced ability to attract investment in the current global economic climate means that the UK industry skills base is diminishing. The numbers of geology and mining engineering students is reducing and those that do train often mi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">grate to other mining jurisdictions where the industry is better supported, salaries are higher and jobs more plentiful – Western Australia, Canada and the Nordic regions.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.What is the impact of the industry of the UK signing up to the EITI?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The signing o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f the EITI by Cameron’s government in June has been very positive for the UK extractive industries.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The signing puts the UK in the position of being a leader in accountability and transparency in the industry and helps to counteract any negative perception</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s that may have been generated by the corporate governance issues previously mentioned; and hopefully goes some way to ensuring that they will never be repeated.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Nordic countries, often regarded as the leaders in ethical areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, Finland, Denmark and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Sweden</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have made </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">announcements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in September</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the UK’s stance on transparency has inspired them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“quickly transpose the EU Accounting and Transparency Directive”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> indicating that this is an area where the UK is seen to be setting the bar.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At the Mining On Top: Africa – London Summit, which was purposely timed to occur the week following the EITI signing at the G8 meeting, the African Mining Ministers were also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">inspired by the UK’s lead, with Kenya declaring a commitment to sign up to the in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">itiative also.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">8.Would increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition from elsewhere or can it be used to make the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although increased regulation would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, I am certain, be opposed by some parts of the industry, other</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> part</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s would welcome it as they are entirely committed to improving the global reputation of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> industry. The fact that we are questioning the impact on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reputation of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">corporate governan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> lapses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> indicates that the UK has a reputation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">worth preserving. C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ompanies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">who have nothing to hide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not put-off by increased regulation so long as it does not add too much expense and is not too onerous.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Differing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> levels of regulation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for different </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organisations might be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> an effective approach. More complex and rigorous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regulation is required </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the larger more complex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organisations with more resources and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">simpler and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">less time consuming for the smaller</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> less complex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cash strapped juniors.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">9.What is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21st Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The competitive landscape for extractives in the 21</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> century is complex. The demand story </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">maintain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s as developi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng nations continue urbanisation and the growing middle classes demand more, smaller, lighter technology and the developed world looks for greener alternatives. At the same time supply is increasingly controlled by less politically stable countries.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Produc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tion costs increase, metal prices fluctuate, shareholders </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and governments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">demand higher returns </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from the industry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and companies concentrate on cost reduction. The large projects are being abandoned by the majors, the junior explorers are struggling to rais</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e cash for their activities and consolidation is occurring as the majority of companies have less than one year’s cash remaining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (IntierraRMG)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All these factors point to future undersupply and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">increased competition for resources. Whilst the boom days of c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ommodities may be over, returns are still significant and, as previously noted the industry delivers returns f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ar beyond the immediate mining companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK must ensure a place at the centre of the industry in order to secure metal supplies and to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">protect the income and jobs that contribute so significantly to the UK economy.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ros C Lund (Ms)</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">22 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>